{{Infobox scientist | name = Alexander Victorovich Fedorov | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=first|1954|11|4}} | birth_place = [[Yelizovo]], [[Russia]] | occupation = [[Media studies|Media educator]], [[theorist]], [[writer]], [[lecturer]], and [[film critic]] | nationality = [[Russia]]n | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = [[Prof. Dr.]] | alma_mater = [[VGIK]] - All-Russian State University of Cinematography, [[Moscow]], [[Russian Academy of Education]], [[Moscow]] | period = 1978-Present | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | subject = Media education, [[media literacy]], [[media culture]], [[media studies]], [[media theories]], [[film history]] | movement = | notableworks = On Media Education ([[Moscow]], 2008 | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | awards = Prize for outstanding contribution to the development of media education [[Russia]], 2007. Prize for Best Media Education Book [[Russia]], 2009. | signature = | website = [http://mediaeducation.ucoz.ru/load/media_education_literacy_in_russia/8 mediaeducation] }}
'''Alexander Victorovich Fedorov''' ({{lang-ru|Александр Викторович Фёдоров}}; born November 4, 1954) is a Russian scientist, teacher, media education specialist, film critic. He completed his Ph.D. [[dissertation]] about [[Media studies|media]] [[education]] (1993) at the [[Russian Academy of Education]] ([[Moscow]]). == Biography == He was the [[president]] of the [[Russian Association for Film and Media Education]] (2003-2014) <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://edu.of.ru/mediaeducation/default.asp?ob_no=794 |title=edu.of.ru |access-date=2009-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818085353/http://edu.of.ru/mediaeducation/default.asp?ob_no=794 |archive-date=2009-08-18 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> and deputy director of the [[Anton Chekhov Taganrog Institute]] (Russia)<ref>[http://tgpi.ru/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=13&Itemid=41 tgpi.ru]</ref> (2005-2018) and main [[editor in chief|editor]] of [[Academic journal|journal]] "Media Education" (‘Mediaobrazovanie’).<ref>[http://mediaeducation.ucoz.ru/load/zhurnal_quot_mediaobrazovanie_quot/6 mediaeducation]</ref> He is also a member of the [[Russian Academy of Film Arts and Science]], [[Russian Union of Filmmakers]],<ref>[http://www.unikino.ru/about/administration.php unikino]</ref> [[CIFEJ]] and [[FIPRESCI]].<ref>[http://www.fipresci.org/people/alexander-fedorov FIPRESCI]</ref> Alexander Fedorov is the [[author]] of 20 books on media education and [[media literacy]] and more than 400 articles (in [[Russian language|Russian]], English, Canadian, French, German, and Norwegian [[media studies]] and media literacy journals).
Since 1997 he has received scientific research grants on [[media culture]] and media education from the President of the [[Russian Federation]],<ref>[http://grants.extech.ru/grants/2003/schools/winers/6.php grants.extech.ru]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://2002.kremlin.ru/pressa/2002040506.html |title=kremlin.ru |access-date=2009-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810161508/http://2002.kremlin.ru/pressa/2002040506.html |archive-date=2011-08-10 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> [[Russian Foundation for Humanities]], Russian Ministry of Education, [[Kennan Institute]] ([[US]]), [[International Research and Exchanges Board|IREX]] (US), [[MacArthure Foundation]] (US), [[German Academic Exchange Service|DAAD]] ([[Germany]]), and others. He was a guest professor and [[research fellow]] in [[Norway Association for Media Education]], [[Oslo]] (1995), [[Central European University]] ([[Budapest]], 1998, 2006), [[Kassel University]] (2000), [[Maison des sciences de l'homme]], [[Paris]] (2002, 2009), [[Kennan Institute]], [[Washington D.C.]] (2003), [[Humboldt University]], [[Berlin]] (2005), [[University of Mainz]] (2010), [[Johann Wolfgang Goethe Universität Frankfurt am Main]] (2014).
