{{Infobox protected area | name =Repetek Biosphere State Reserve | iucn_category = | photo =Takirs of Karakum Desert.jpg | photo_caption = | map = Turkmenistan | map_caption = Map of [[Turkmenistan]] | map_width = | relief = 1 | location = [[Lebap Province]], [[Turkmenistan]] | nearest_city = [[Türkmenabat]] | coordinates = {{coord|38.606|N|63.214|E|region:TM-L|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coords_ref = <ref>{{Cite web| url=http://protectedplanet.net/sites/Repetek_Zapovednik_Unescomab_Biosphere_Reserve| title=Repetek Zapovednik Unesco Mab Biosphere Reserve| work=protectedplanet.net}}</ref> | area = {{Convert|346|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} | established = 1928 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = }}
'''Repetek Biosphere State Reserve''', often referred to as '''Repetek Nature or Desert Reserve''', ({{lang-tk|Repetek goraghanasy}}, ''Репетек горагханасы'') is a [[desert]] [[Protected areas of Turkmenistan|nature reserve]] (''[[zapovednik]]'') of [[Turkmenistan]], located in [[Lebap Province]], East [[Karakum Desert]], near [[Amu Darya]]. It is located approximately {{Convert|70|km|mi|abbr=on}} south from [[Türkmenabat]] and is known for its ''zemzen'' (desert monitor which is [[Varanus griseus]]). Established in 1928 for the study and preservation of a sand-desert ecosystem, it covers an area of {{Convert|346|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}.
==Geography==
The landscape of the reserve is arid, with extensive ridged sand dunes some {{Convert|15|-|20|m|ft|abbr=on}} in height and {{Convert|8|-|10|m|ft|abbr=on}} in length in many areas, large areas of sand dune and valley-like depressions.{{Sfn|UNESCO}} [[Haloxylon aphyllum|Black saxaul]] (''Haloxylon aphyllum''), rare to most part of Central Asia covers more than {{Convert|1470|km2|mi2|abbr=on}}, approximately 4.5% of the territory of the reserve. The soils have sandy subsoils, but some "21 trees, 104 grasses, 8 mushrooms, 1 moss, 68 soil algae and 197 fungi" grow within the reserve.{{Sfn|UNESCO}}
==History==
The Repetek sandy desert scientific station was organized in 1912 by the decision of the [[Russian Geographical Society]], and the reserve was established in 1928 on the base of the scientific station.<ref>{{harvnb|Sokolov|Veiisov|Gunin|1990| p=182}}</ref> During the Soviet period the reserve belongs to the Institute of Deserts of the Turkmen SSR Academy of Sciences. The list of scientific publications concerning with the Repetek sandy desert station and the biosphere reserve since 1982 to 1991 consists of about 250 papers (30% on landscape structure and geography, 20% on botany and 50% on zoology).{{Sfn|Kuzmenko, Veiisov|1992|p=76}}
The Institute of Deserts, Flora and Fauna of the Academy of Sciences of Turkmenistan was established in 1962 to study ways of reclaiming desert land for economic use in the reserve.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/498342/Repetek-Nature-Reserve Encyclopædia Britannica]</ref>
==Environmental protection==
The Repetek Biosphere State Reserve is part of an [[Important Bird Area]] (IBA) and since 1979 has been an under the monitoring of [[UNESCO]] but "the site is under the administration of the Ministry of Nature Protection of Turkmenistan".{{Sfn|UNESCO}} The reserve "supports the most complete assemblage of bird species typical of the sand desert of the Karakum" and "has an important population of [[Goitered Gazelle]] (Gazella subgutturosa) which is listed as Vulnerable (VU) in the [[IUCN Red List]]".{{Sfn|UNESCO}}
==Climate==
Repetek Biosphere State Reserve has a [[desert climate]] ([[Köppen climate classification]] ''BWk''), with cool winters and very hot summers. Rainfall is generally light and erratic, and occurs mainly in the winter and autumn months.
