|{{nowrap|[[Arizona]]}}
|[[Phoenix Lights]]
|The Phoenix Lights, sometimes referred to as "The Lights Over Phoenix", is the popular name given to a series of optical phenomena that took place in the sky over the US states of [[Arizona]] and [[Nevada]] on March 13, 1997. Lights of varying descriptions were seen by thousands of people between 19:30 and 22:30 MST, in a space of about 300 miles, from the Nevada line, through [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], to the edge of [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]]. UFO proponents claimed they were part of aircraft unknown to man, while the USAF identified them as flares dropped by A-10 Warthog aircraft which were on training exercises. In 2007, former Arizona governor [[Fife Symington]] came forward and admitted that he had seen "a massive, delta-shaped craft silently navigate over Squaw Peak" in 1997.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/TECH/science/11/09/simington.ufocommentary/| author=Fife Symington| title=Symington: I saw a UFO in the Arizona sky| publisher=CNN| date=November 9, 2007}}</ref>
